== Every smooth manifold admits a Riemannian metric ==
Theorem: Every smooth manifold admits a (non-canonical) Riemannian metric.

This is a fundamental result. Although much of the basic theory of Riemannian metrics can be developed using only that a smooth manifold is a locally Euclidean topological space, for this result it is necessary to use that smooth manifolds are Hausdorff and paracompact. The reason is that the proof makes use of a partition of unity. 
Let formula_149 be a smooth manifold and formula_150 a locally finite atlas so that formula_151 are open subsets and formula_152 are diffeomorphisms. Such an atlas exists because the manifold is paracompact.

Let formula_153 be a differentiable partition of unity subordinate to the given atlas, i.e. such that formula_154 for all formula_155.

Define a Riemannian metric formula_11 on formula_2 by
: formula_158
where
:formula_159
Here formula_67 is the Euclidean metric on formula_142 and formula_162 is its pullback along formula_163. While formula_164 is only defined on formula_165, the product formula_166 is defined and smooth on formula_2 since formula_154. It takes the value 0 outside of formula_165. Because the atlas is locally finite, at every point the sum contains only finitely many nonzero terms, so the sum converges. It is straightforward to check that formula_11 is a Riemannian metric.
An alternative proof uses the Whitney embedding theorem to embed formula_2 into Euclidean space and then pulls back the metric from Euclidean space to formula_2. On the other hand, the Nash embedding theorem states that, given any smooth Riemannian manifold formula_173 there is an embedding formula_174 for some formula_79 such that the pullback by formula_176 of the standard Riemannian metric on formula_177 is formula_178 That is, the entire structure of a smooth Riemannian manifold can be encoded by a diffeomorphism to a certain embedded submanifold of some Euclidean space. Therefore, one could argue that nothing can be gained from the consideration of abstract smooth manifolds and their Riemannian metrics. However, there are many natural smooth Riemannian manifolds, such as the set of rotations of three-dimensional space and hyperbolic space, of which any representation as a submanifold of Euclidean space will fail to represent their remarkable symmetries and properties as clearly as their abstract presentations do.

== Metric space structure ==
An &quot;admissible curve&quot; is a piecewise smooth curve formula_179 whose velocity formula_180 is nonzero everywhere it is defined. The nonnegative function formula_181 is defined on the interval formula_182 except for at finitely many points. The length formula_183 of an admissible curve formula_179 is defined as
: formula_185
The integrand is bounded and continuous except at finitely many points, so it is integrable. For &quot;formula_19&quot; a connected Riemannian manifold, define formula_187 by
: formula_188
Theorem: formula_189 is a metric space, and the metric topology on formula_189 coincides with the topology on formula_2.
In verifying that formula_189 satisfies all of the axioms of a metric space, the most difficult part is checking that formula_193 implies formula_194. Verification of the other metric space axioms is omitted.

There must be some precompact open set around &quot;p&quot; which every curve from &quot;p&quot; to &quot;q&quot; must escape. By selecting this open set to be contained in a coordinate chart, one can reduce the claim to the well-known fact that, in Euclidean geometry, the shortest curve between two points is a line. In particular, as seen by the Euclidean geometry of a coordinate chart around &quot;p&quot;, any curve from &quot;p&quot; to &quot;q&quot; must first pass though a certain &quot;inner radius.&quot; The assumed continuity of the Riemannian metric &quot;g&quot; only allows this &quot;coordinate chart geometry&quot; to distort the &quot;true geometry&quot; by some bounded factor.

To be precise, let formula_120 be a smooth coordinate chart with formula_196 and formula_197 Let formula_198 be an open subset of formula_30 with formula_200 By continuity of formula_11 and compactness of formula_202 there is a positive number formula_203 such that formula_204 for any formula_205 and any formula_206 where formula_207 denotes the Euclidean norm induced by the local coordinates. Let &quot;R&quot; denote formula_208.
Now, given any admissible curve formula_209 from &quot;p&quot; to &quot;q&quot;, there must be some minimal formula_210 such that formula_211 clearly formula_212

The length of formula_213 is at least as large as the restriction of formula_213 to formula_215 So
: formula_216
The integral which appears here represents the Euclidean length of a curve from 0 to formula_217, and so it is greater than or equal to &quot;R&quot;. So we conclude formula_218

The observation about comparison between lengths measured by &quot;g&quot; and Euclidean lengths measured in a smooth coordinate chart, also verifies that the metric space topology of formula_189 coincides with the original topological space structure of formula_2. 
Although the length of a curve is given by an explicit formula, it is generally impossible to write out the distance function formula_221 by any explicit means. In fact, if formula_2 is compact, there always exist points where formula_223 is non-differentiable, and it can be remarkably difficult to even determine the location or nature of these points, even in seemingly simple cases such as when formula_19 is an ellipsoid.

If one works with Riemannian metrics that are merely continuous but possibly not smooth, the length of an admissible curve and the Riemannian distance function are defined exactly the same, and, as before, formula_189 is a metric space and the metric topology on formula_189 coincides with the topology on formula_2.

=== Diameter ===
The &quot;diameter&quot; of the metric space formula_189 is
: formula_229
The Hopf–Rinow theorem shows that if formula_189 is complete and has finite diameter, it is compact. Conversely, if formula_189 is compact, then the function formula_223 has a maximum, since it is a continuous function on a compact metric space. This proves the following.
: If formula_189 is complete, then it is compact if and only if it has finite diameter.
This is not the case without the completeness assumption; for counterexamples one could consider any open bounded subset of a Euclidean space with the standard Riemannian metric. It is also not true that &quot;any&quot; complete metric space of finite diameter must be compact; it matters that the metric space came from a Riemannian manifold.

== Connections, geodesics, and curvature ==

=== Connections ===
An (affine) connection is an additional structure on a Riemannian manifold that defines differentiation of one vector field with respect to another. Connections contain geometric data, and two Riemannian manifolds with different connections have different geometry.

Let formula_234 denote the space of vector fields on formula_2. An &quot;(affine) connection&quot;
